  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Turning Scores into Weights"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After computing the scaled dot-product scores S = QKᵀ / √d_k, we need to convert each row into a probability distribution — a set of non-negative weights that sum to 1. Softmax is the standard choice, and for good reason: it is differentiable, amplifies differences, and produces a valid convex combination of value vectors."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Softmax Function"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Applied row-wise to the score matrix, softmax converts each row of n raw scores into n attention weights:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\alpha_{ij} = \\frac{\\exp(S_{ij})}{\\sum_{k=1}^{n} \\exp(S_{ik})}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Every α_ij ≥ 0 (exp is always positive)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Each row sums to exactly 1: Σ_j α_ij = 1."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A score gap of Δ translates to a weight ratio of e^Δ — e.g., Δ = 2 → 7.4× more weight."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Diagram showing a row of raw scores being exponentiated, summed, and normalised into probability weights, then combined as a weighted sum of value vectors"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Weighted Sum of Values"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The attention weights α_i· are used to form a weighted average of all value vectors:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{output}_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{n} \\alpha_{ij}\\, V_j = A_i \\cdot V"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In matrix form for all positions simultaneously: output = A · V, where A ∈ ℝ^(n×n) and V ∈ ℝ^(n×d_v). Each output token is a blend of all value vectors, weighted by how relevant each position was. The position with the highest softmax weight dominates; low-weight positions contribute but are diluted."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Code: Softmax and Weighted Sum"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\n# scores: (batch, heads, seq_len, seq_len) — scaled dot products\nscores = torch.tensor([[0.3, 2.4, 1.6, 0.0, 0.1]])  # one row, 5 positions\n\n# softmax converts each row to a probability distribution\nweights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\nprint(weights.round(decimals=2))\n# tensor([[0.07, 0.57, 0.25, 0.05, 0.06]])\nprint(weights.sum(dim=-1))  # tensor([1.0000])\n\n# weighted sum of value vectors\nd_v = 4\nV = torch.randn(1, 5, d_v)        # (batch=1, seq=5, d_v=4)\nweights_3d = weights.unsqueeze(-1)  # (1, 1, 5, 1) for broadcasting\n# or equivalently: output = weights @ V\noutput = (weights.unsqueeze(0) @ V)  # (1, 1, d_v)\nprint(output.shape)  # torch.Size([1, 1, 4])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Numerical Stability: The Log-Sum-Exp Trick"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Large raw scores (e.g., s = 1000) cause exp(s) to overflow to inf in float32. The standard fix subtracts the row maximum before exponentiating — a mathematically equivalent transformation since softmax is translation-invariant:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{softmax}(s_j) = \\frac{\\exp(s_j - m)}{\\sum_k \\exp(s_k - m)}, \\quad m = \\max_k s_k"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\ndef stable_softmax(scores):\n    \"\"\"Numerically stable softmax along last dimension.\"\"\"\n    m = scores.max(dim=-1, keepdim=True).values\n    exp_shifted = (scores - m).exp()\n    return exp_shifted / exp_shifted.sum(dim=-1, keepdim=True)\n\n# Demonstrate: large scores that would otherwise overflow\ndangerous = torch.tensor([900.0, 901.0, 899.0])\nprint(torch.softmax(dangerous, dim=0))          # handles it (PyTorch applies trick internally)\nprint(stable_softmax(dangerous))                # same result, explicit implementation\n# tensor([0.2119, 0.5761, 0.2119]) — safe and correct\n\n# F.softmax already does this internally — you don't need to implement it yourself"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PyTorch's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "F.softmax"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " applies this trick internally, so you do not need to subtract the max manually when using the standard library."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Softmax Rather Than Other Normalizations?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Alternative"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Problem"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Divide by sum (ℓ1 norm)"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Negative scores → negative weights; output not a valid mixture"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Sigmoid per score"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Weights don't sum to 1; can't interpret as attention allocation"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Sparsemax (hard top-k)"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Sets low scores to exactly 0; useful in some settings but not standard"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Uniform (equal weights)"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Ignores the Q·K scores entirely; no selective attention possible"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Softmax in the Full Attention Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\ndef attention(Q, K, V, mask=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Single-head attention.\n    Q, K: (batch, seq, d_k)\n    V:    (batch, seq, d_v)\n    Returns: (batch, seq, d_v), (batch, seq, seq)\n    \"\"\"\n    d_k = Q.size(-1)\n\n    # Step 1: scaled dot-product scores\n    scores = torch.bmm(Q, K.transpose(1, 2)) / d_k**0.5  # (batch, seq, seq)\n\n    # Step 2: optional mask (e.g., causal, padding)\n    if mask is not None:\n        scores = scores.masked_fill(~mask, float('-inf'))\n\n    # Step 3: softmax → attention weights\n    weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)  # rows sum to 1; -inf → 0 after exp\n\n    # Step 4: weighted sum of values\n    output = torch.bmm(weights, V)       # (batch, seq, d_v)\n    return output, weights\n\n# Demo\nbatch, seq, d_k, d_v = 2, 6, 32, 32\nQ = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_k)\nK = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_k)\nV = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_v)\nout, attn = attention(Q, K, V)\nprint(out.shape)    # (2, 6, 32)\nprint(attn[0].sum(dim=-1))  # all 1.0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Why -inf works for masking:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " When a position is masked to −∞, exp(−∞) = 0, so it contributes nothing to the softmax denominator and gets weight 0. The remaining positions' weights still sum to 1 — the distribution simply ignores the masked positions."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradient of Softmax"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Jacobian of softmax at output α is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\frac{\\partial \\alpha_i}{\\partial s_j} = \\alpha_i(\\delta_{ij} - \\alpha_j)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is non-zero for all (i, j) pairs, meaning every score receives a gradient signal — even scores for low-weight positions. The gradient magnitude shrinks when weights are very concentrated (near 0 or 1), which is the vanishing gradient concern that the √d_k scaling prevents by keeping scores in a moderate range."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
